%% AEAD Sequence Diagram - Encryption and Verification Flow
sequenceDiagram
  autonumber
  participant S as Sender
  participant A as Attacker (optional)
  participant R as Receiver

  Note over S: Choose unique nonce N for this message<br/>N must be different for each message using key K<br/>Example: counter (1, 2, 3...) or random<br/>K is shared beforehand and reused for many messages
  
  S->>S: 1. Encrypt: C = Encrypt with K, N, P
  Note over S: 2. Create Tag using MAC algorithm (e.g., HMAC-SHA256, Poly1305)<br/>T = MAC with K, N, C, AD<br/>Process: Hash function combines all inputs with key K<br/>Output: Fixed-size tag T that binds all data to K
  
  S-->>R: Send N, AD, C, T
  
  Note over A: ⚠️ AD is plaintext - attacker can read it<br/>Use AD for NON-SECRET metadata only<br/>Examples: headers, request ID, timestamp<br/>Never put passwords or secrets in AD!<br/><br/>Attacker can modify C or AD<br/>BUT cannot create valid tag without K<br/>MAC is one-way: cannot reverse to find K
  
  Note over R: 3. Recompute Tag using same MAC algorithm<br/>T' = MAC with K, N, C, AD<br/>Uses same hash function with received data
  R->>R: 4. Compare: Is T' equal to T?
  
  alt Tags Match (T' = T)
    Note over R: ✅ No tampering detected<br/>Data is authentic and unchanged
    R->>R: 5. Decrypt: P = Decrypt with K, N, C
    R-->>R: Output plaintext P
  else Tags Do Not Match (T' ≠ T)
    Note over R: ❌ Tampering detected!<br/>• C, AD, or N was modified, OR<br/>• Wrong key K used<br/>• Attacker cannot forge valid tag
    R-->>R: REJECT - no plaintext revealed
  end
